# name: test_error_message[mixed_bool_op.py]
  '''
  mixed_bool_op.py:6:13: error: `or` on unrelated types has no single C++ type
  
    6 |     label = count() or "none"
      |             ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
  
    help: `or` returns one of its operands, so both sides need the same type.
            Use it directly in a condition instead:
            if count or fallback:
  
  '''
# ---
# name: test_error_message[object_element.py]
  '''
  object_element.py:2:15: error: no C++ equivalent for the type `object`
  
    2 |     print(any([False, True]))
      |               ^^^^^^^^^^^^^
  
    help: `object` is what mypy infers when the elements disagree, or when a literal goes straight into something taking Iterable[object].
            Name it first so the element type comes from the values:
            flags = [False, True]
            print(any(flags))
  
  '''
